I Printed the thick plate as the base, and found some slight lifting of the corners during the printing, however the structure was rigid enough not to deform the printing layer at the hot end. Printing the thin plate as the base might also work but I don't know. The hexagon cells are pitched at 3 Degrees so if you choose to use it to store something else, you may use it resting on the thick base and the Hex cells opening horizontally instead of vertically.

The print took about 30 hours to finish at 100% Prusa normal speed.

Hex Cell Copy and Paste

I created a single hex cell, cloned it and used copy and paste tools in Fusion 360 to create an array of cells, I then combined them all into a single object, and rotated that object 3 Degrees. I then added a couple of rectangular plates for a sturdy base and a thin back to seal the cell on one side.

description.text:
Update 4/28/17
Finally had the chance to authentically test this. I cut the parachute off of one of these guys: http://a.co/5VXAKWL and it worked even better than I expected. It fell softly and did not break the lens protection posts even though they are supposed to be sacrificial. Of course then we dropped the camera twice without a parachute just for fun. We ended up with a lawn dart style landing. The sacrificial posts did not last for those drops.

The only criticism is the camera drops and has to gain a lot of speed before it stabilizes. I can't rifle the fins without ruining the video. Maybe if the fins were larger it would stabilize faster.

Parachute 1: https://youtu.be/km4F8nngSJ8
Parachute 2: https://youtu.be/sT6TsPxN_LM
Free Fall 1: https://youtu.be/EVD1WzBlLs0
Free Fall 2: https://youtu.be/IMJrAsLFvWk

Original I'm working on a project that drops eggs from a drone and thought it would be fun to get an eggs eye view. Instead of risking a GoPro I searched "action camera" on amazon and decided it was worth risking $40 that I might break this: http://a.co/0kervw1

I'm going to attach a parachute and drop this at least three times, two with the parachute and once without a parachute. The posts that extend past the lens are not visible by the camera and are guaranteed to break instantly due to the layer orientation. (Delamination) I don't care though it will be a fun experiment!

I printed this with two perimeters and 10% infill. Slip the camera in and use an M6 screw to hold the case to the camera and tie the parachute on.

I've included the STL files for the case and one for the camera model. Note that the M6 screw is centered 39mm up from the bottom of the camera.

description.text:
(for now keep crop factor >0.9 in customizer - for reason see below)
.
This is a generator for horns with tractrix crossection.
Those are not the same as spherical wave horns. See here:
https://www.grc.com/acoustics/an-introduction-to-horn-theory.pdf
http://audioxpress.com/ax-supplementary-material/
under: Horn Theory: An Introduction, Part 1
http://www.audioxpress.com/files/2008/03/kolbrek2884.pdf
and: Horn Theory: An Introduction, Part 2
http://www.audioxpress.com/files/2008/04/kolbrek2885.pdf
Horns act as acoustic impedance matching transformators
transformating high pressure low speed to low pressure high speed sound waves or vice versa.
.
Note that the sizes that are printable on common personal 3D printers are only suitable for rather high frequencies (even for whistles).
Well as it turns out low frequencies get amplified as well.
See: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:389700
.
Example horn:
cutoff frequency: 4500Hz
inlet inner diameter: 20mm
inlet outer diameter: 24mm
inlet pipe length: 5mm
horn length cropped to: 80%
cropped horn mouth diameter: 126.5mm
complete horn length: 129.9mm
tractrix segment length: 124.9mm
.
known problem: customizer can't deal with this file :(
found out: crop factor above 0.9000 works

It's a Tachikoma! Rather than buying a Tachikoma figure I thought it was about time I designed my own (Motoko not included)

Credit to MarcRichmond (http://marcrichmond.deviantart.com/art/Tachikoma-FT-CR-194128872) for the blueprint this model is based on. Really nice piece.

Varies

Notes:

Printed in ABS then acetone vapour smoothed.

Large parts printed at 0.2 mm base layer height then using Slic3r's variable layer heights to increase resolution to 0.05 mm layers on upper curved surfaces. Small parts printed at 0.15 mm resolution.

Supports were only used on the abdomen shell parts to support the tops of the openings for the side doors and underside eye section.

• A_Tachikoma_Single_Body_Solid
  • B_Tachikoma_Single_Body_Hollow

These files have the Tachikoma as a single body with no interfering faces. The hollow version has the abdomen section hollowed out to shift the centre of mass forward. Not sure that it's absolutely necessary to prevent tipping backward but it does slightly reduce the amount of material required.

• C_Tachikoma...

Basic CAD model split into sections, bodies combined and ball and socket joints modeled in. No further preparation for printing so likely to need supports. Joints are not designed to snap together and hold, they must be glued into a fixed pose.

description.header: Multi Part Figure split up for Printing
description.text:
• D_Tachikoma...

This is the model split up as I printed it with minimal supports and optimal build orientation.

Multiple parts:

  • Alignment_Pin x6 (one in each leg and each arm)
  • Arm_Part_01 x2
  • Head_Part_03 x4
  • All Leg Parts x4

Building a Tachikoma from these files requires a lot of finishing work, all of my pieces were vapour smoothed then glued together. Gaps were filled and sanded before painting.

Some parts have two versions, one the basic part and one with a built in 0.2 mm brim for better bed adhesion.

• Tachikoma_ASM_Multiple_Bodies

Contains all of the individual bodies from the basic CAD model before being split and combined for printing. Contains both foot versions. Included for anyone who wants to play around with the model but not ideal for printing without some preparation work.

title: E3D hotend mount for RepRap Mendel

description.text:
This is a model that allows you to mount an E3D hotend to a regular RepRap Mendel 3D printer.

Please be aware:

This design has captured nuts. Either print the version that allows you to place them in post-print (listed as Hotend_holder_plate_post_placeable_nuts_final.stl), or you will be required to pause the print and place them in before resuming, which tends to result in a stronger print.

Captured nut and bolt Sizes

This design uses three bolts to attach the outer part to the inner part, these bolts have a diameter of 3.8mm, thread length of ~15.5mm (no unthreaded section). The corresponding nuts have an across flat measure of 7mm and are 2.9mm deep

Attachment to the printer is designed to work with the original nuts and bolts from the printer as it is a replacement for the plastic mount in which the hotend sits. The fan can be attached using the screws that are normally used to attach it to the original (usually blue) fan mount for the E3D hotend.

The layer bonding is important and many materials are not so easy in this case. ABS, Nylon and some more can make problems if the temperature is low or too much part cooling is applied. This easy part is just based a two thin walls and shows you:

  • the bonding if you break (with pliers) or walk and bend it (try out different layer hight)
  • stringing problems between the two cylinders
  • temperatur adjustments as the part is high enough that you can modify the temp during the print.

The small base between the cylinders help to keep it on the build plate, I do not adding any brim to my tests. This part is optimized for 0.4mm nozzles, for other sizes you have probably to scale it.

Have you seen my other easy material calibration part http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1023717, downloaded more than 1,000 times so far?

Enjoy!

text = Karlie

In the building of my DIY NAS: 2017 Edition using the SilverStone DS380 case, I noticed that my hard disk drive temperatures were running a few degrees higher than I was comfortable with.

I wound up reading a FreeNAS forum post describing blocking an air gap at the bottom of the case's drive cage and asked myself "Why not design a duct that screws into the case's 120mm cooling fans?"

After a few minutes with my calipers, a few revisions later, and after stamping my face on the thing, I had a closed the majority of the SilverStone DS380's air gap with the duct.

No 3D Printer? No problem! My friend Pat is selling the Cooling Fan Duct For Silverstone DS380B Case on his Tindie store for quite a bit cheaper than the few 3D printing services I compared it to.

description.text:
There are a couple cool Helicarrier quadrotors out there people have made, but none as small or as accurate as this one I believe.

Although I designed it with the Hubsan X4 in mind, this is much bigger, measuring in at about 300mm/11.8" long, and should weigh in at about 150 grams for just the frame. I think it will fly with the stock motors, but you may need to upgrade them with something like these or these.

I'll be honest - I'm not good at electronics and blew $60 after killing two separate Hubsan X4 control boards trying to modify them for this - so I don't know if it'll actually work. I wish the best of luck on whoever tries.

For the non-flying, more accurate version of the Helicarrier, check here. This version's hull is a bit "slimmed down," and the "turbines" are obviously more open to allow for real rotors.
